<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Telangana</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">The <em>Kohinoor of Deccan</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Telangana — India's youngest state, born on June 2, 2014 after a decades-long people's movement — is one of the subcontinent's most layered and magnificent civilizations. Its capital Hyderabad, the City of Pearls, was once the richest city in the world under the Nizam of Hyderabad — whose personal wealth in the 1940s was estimated at 2% of US GDP, making him the wealthiest person on earth. The Golconda Fort was the source of the world's most legendary diamonds — the Kohinoor, the Hope Diamond, the Regent and the Nassak all came from its mines. Telangana sits on the ancient Deccan Plateau — a billion-year-old volcanic landscape of granite boulders, stepwells, reservoirs (tanks) and black cotton soil. The Kakatiyas — one of India's greatest dynasties — ruled from Warangal between the 12th and 14th centuries, building the magnificent Warangal Fort, the Thousand Pillar Temple and the extraordinary Ramappa Temple, now a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Telangana's culture is a magnificent fusion: Telugu literary tradition stretching 1,000 years, Urdu Nawabi refinement, Deccani cuisine that blends Persian, Turkish and Telugu flavors, folk art traditions of extraordinary vitality and the Bathukamma festival — an ocean of flowers celebrated by Telangana's women with a fervor found nowhere else. Hyderabad today is India's tech capital, the home of HITEC City, Genome Valley and global campuses — a city that holds antiquity and modernity in glittering tension. Telangana is the pearl — lustrous, layered, and irreducibly its own.</p>
</section>

